WHEREAS, he also had the honor of interviewing President Barack Obama at the White
House, a highlight of his already illustrious career; and
WHEREAS, Richard Ransom revitalized ABC 24's This Week, transforming it into a
must-watch program for both viewers and community leaders; and
WHEREAS, with authenticity at the heart of his work, Mr. Ransom has been deeply
committed to presenting a balanced and honest portrayal of Memphis, particularly when
addressing the complexities of crime; rejecting the "crime all the time" narrative, he has
championed transparency and context, ensuring viewers receive the full story; and
WHEREAS, he has also been a vocal advocate for the community, holding politicians
accountable and celebrating the generosity of Memphians through initiatives such as the "Pass
It On" segment; his efforts to improve public health standards, including urging local restaurants
to "Clean Up!" after health inspection failures, have further cemented his legacy; and
WHEREAS, Richard Ransom epitomizes the spirit and commitment to community that
are characteristic of a true Tennessean; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Ransom's dedication to journalism has inspired his colleagues and
elevated the standards of reporting in Memphis, and it is our privilege to recognize his important
contributions to this State and its citizens; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, that we honor and
commend Richard Ransom for his countless contributions to journalism and his service to the
citizens of Memphis, extending to him our best wishes for much continued success.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy.
